[{"id":27339,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Gabriel phthalimide synthesis is used to prepare <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math> aliphatic/alicyclic amine in common.</p><p>Hence, amine which can synthesised by Gabriel phthalimide synthesis method is:</p><p>(A)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Me</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>(B)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>(C)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27340,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6bc28de3-7660-4672-b0e1-8f1a2cc8081f-image.png\" style=\"width: 143px; height: 154px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NHCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4b10c515-7dbc-456c-a02d-f7e2f99fe3f5-image.png\" style=\"width: 291px; height: 182px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d0464f2c-761a-4cd5-9883-2d4758abd1f3-image.png\" style=\"width: 144px; height: 199px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;"],"answer":0,"solution":"&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27279,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/18ca611e-2d72-411a-a04d-e50050fef593-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6b31a9bb-d023-436b-85f1-33e28b267017-image.png\" style=\"width: 101px; height: 160px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fd4b3517-7eb2-4163-aadd-2d0405576489-image.png\" style=\"width: 76px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f252c50d-408f-4d15-a87d-9c981cb02774-image.png\" style=\"width: 77px; height: 100px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Cyclic amines are more basic than open chain amines of same degree. Because open chain amines undergo umbrella inversion which decreases the basic nature. Hence, among the given compounds, quinuclidine is strongest base.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f252c50d-408f-4d15-a87d-9c981cb02774-image.png\" style=\"width: 77px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>And also quinuclidine is more basic and more nucleophilic than triethylamine,&nbsp;because of lesser steric hindrance in quinuclidine than in triethylamine. Lesser steric hindrance in quinuclidine is due to all the alkyl groups are &ldquo;tucked&rdquo; back and Nitrogen is more exposed and can easily donate its lone pair electrons.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27315,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/78ce8f7c-9cd6-468f-a207-b2d5e954732a-image.png\" style=\"width: 321px; height: 115px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eee17136-173e-45d8-9f47-cb954f8539de-image.png\" style=\"width: 315px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/952bfbd2-1784-4bd0-b7ca-9d887fb25891-image.png\" style=\"width: 320px; height: 86px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bf06ab2f-f728-4629-a1dc-e7665113add2-image.png\" style=\"width: 312px; height: 126px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>One very common reaction of amide is Hoffmann&#39;s bromamide reaction in which amide get converted into amine having one carbon less than amide. For this reaction reagent is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>KOH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>or</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>KOBr</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.</p><p>Lithium aluminium hydride is very strong reducing agent which will convert amide into amine. Number of carbon is same in both amide and amine.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f4f81bd7-8d09-4f11-9cde-e248ad33468a-image.png\" style=\"width: 445px; height: 322px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27379,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["Sandmeyer's reaction","Carbylamine reaction","Idoform test","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The Hinsberg test, which can distinguish primary, secondary, and tertiary amines, is based upon sulfonamide formation. In the Hinsberg test, an amine is reacted with benzene sulfonyl chloride. If a product forms, the amine is either a primary or secondary amine, because tertiary amines do not form stable sulfonamides. If the sulfonamide that forms dissolves in aqueous sodium hydroxide solution, it is a primary amine. If the sulfonamide is insoluble in aqueous sodium hydroxide, it is a secondary amine</p><p>Benzene sulphonyl chloride&nbsp;is Hinsberg reagent.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27253,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/580b9c54-0c04-43e8-a367-d8ebb460a38c.png\" style=\"width: 421px; height: 129px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3576975d-61d5-44e0-96a8-96266ff3f443.png\" style=\"width: 429px; height: 123px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0d0346ca-5c02-4784-86de-3bd4ea7739b2.png\" style=\"width: 453px; height: 108px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2b033885-4516-4f55-bef7-5619bef110c6.png\" style=\"width: 421px; height: 112px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The reaction of aniline (aromatic amine) with nitrous acid results in the diazonium salt formation which is benzene diazonium chloride.When benzene diazonium chloride reacts with N, N - dimethyl aniline at ice cold condition gives p - dimethyl aminoazobenzene. It is an example of coupling reaction.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/59b0b118-3c19-4176-9fa4-be97b865961f.png\" style=\"width: 758px; height: 206px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27328,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#168;</mo></mover><msub><mi>HC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#168;</mo></mover></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#168;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#168;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>For the given compounds:&nbsp;</p><p>(1)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e263173d-909f-477b-90bc-ec1bd25df1b2-image.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 65px;\" />;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>.</mo></math> on Nitrogen is&nbsp;delocalised.</p><p>(2)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/073a483b-cd08-4eec-a6c0-8d8df26cf8f6-d6f62aed-92db-4e8a-acb0-2f592075a93c-image.png\" style=\"width: 211px; height: 73px;\" />;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>.</mo></math> on Nitrogen is&nbsp;localised.</p><p>(3)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4ddce132-6826-4d9a-a456-4695dd073efb-image.png\" style=\"width: 211px; height: 68px;\" />;&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>.</mo></math> on Nitrogen is&nbsp;delocalised due to conjugation with both&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/998c953f-e3de-420e-98ee-1511086574cb-image.png\" style=\"width: 54px; height: 59px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>(Hence least basic)</p><p>(4) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#168;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>.</mo></math> on Nitrogen&nbsp;is localised.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27213,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{B} \\gt \\mathrm{E} \\gt \\mathrm{D} \\gt \\mathrm{A} \\gt \\mathrm{C}$","$\\mathrm{E} \\gt \\mathrm{D} \\gt \\mathrm{B} \\gt \\mathrm{A} \\gt \\mathrm{C}$","$\\mathrm{E} \\gt \\mathrm{D} \\gt \\mathrm{A} \\gt \\mathrm{B} \\gt \\mathrm{C}$","$\\mathrm{E} \\gt \\mathrm{A} \\gt \\mathrm{D} \\gt \\mathrm{C} \\gt \\mathrm{B}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{E} \\gt \\mathrm{D} \\gt \\mathrm{B} \\gt \\mathrm{A} \\gt \\mathrm{C}$<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/S8w6ihOreSjQmXOIHCCH5LcEthHnIfDK7Guvh7DkXGw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27288,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8b3bd3a6-b5fa-4bf8-913d-167c14b08b8f-image.png\" style=\"width: 210px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/51f318b9-7e38-47e9-a643-df5eca011483-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0a206bfc-a194-4e98-8241-86aca7e4e32e-image.png\" style=\"width: 283px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a284b626-d8b8-4745-b13f-4958282e31fd-image.png\" style=\"width: 214px; height: 120px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In aniline&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a strong activating group. So, on direct bromination, substitution will occur at all ortho and para positions. And also we can not use lewis acid since it will react with lewis acid. But if we first convert this into amide then only para substitution will be major product.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cac2fee0-4bb6-437d-b296-0e7a3b66c868-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 300px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null}]